.TH "MAP.SET" "3JS" "September 22, 2025" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
Map.set \- Map.prototype.set()
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]set()\f[B]\f[R] method of \f[CR]Map\f[R] instances adds a
new entry with a specified key and value to this \f[CR]Map\f[R], or
updates an existing entry if the key already exists.
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] map = \f[B]new\f[R] Map();
map.set(\(dqbar\(dq, \(dqfoo\(dq);

console.log(map.get(\(dqbar\(dq));
\f[I]// Expected output: \(dqfoo\(dq\f[R]

console.log(map.get(\(dqbaz\(dq));
\f[I]// Expected output: undefined\f[R]
.EE
.SH SYNTAX
.IP
.EX
set(key, value)
.EE
.SS Parameters
.TP
\f[B]key\f[R]
The key of the entry to add to or modify within the \f[CR]Map\f[R]
object.
Can be any value.
Object keys are compared by reference, not by value.
.TP
\f[B]value\f[R]
The value of the entry to add to or modify within the \f[CR]Map\f[R]
object.
Can be any value.
.SS Return value
The \f[CR]Map\f[R] object.
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Using set()
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] myMap = \f[B]new\f[R] Map();

\f[I]// Add new elements to the map\f[R]
myMap.set(\(dqbar\(dq, \(dqfoo\(dq);
myMap.set(1, \(dqfoobar\(dq);

\f[I]// Update an element in the map\f[R]
myMap.set(\(dqbar\(dq, \(dqbaz\(dq);
.EE
.SS Using the set() with chaining
Since the \f[CR]set()\f[R] method returns back the same \f[CR]Map\f[R]
object, you can chain the method call like below:
.IP
.EX
\f[I]// Add new elements to the map with chaining.\f[R]
myMap.set(\(dqbar\(dq, \(dqfoo\(dq).set(1, \(dqfoobar\(dq).set(2, \(dqbaz\(dq);
.EE
